******
[3]
Date: Thu 11 Nov 2021
Source: Kazakhstan Today [in Russian, machine trans., edited]
https://www.kt.kz/rus/society/v_sele_kostanayskoy_oblasti_vveden_karantin_iz-za_vspyshki_1377924484.html


Quarantine was introduced in the village of Zhaltyrkol, Kostanay region due to an outbreak of anthrax among cattle, Kazakhstan Today reports. Quarantine was established on the property of Batalinskoye LLP [limited liability partnership] in the village of Zhaltyrkol, Arkhangelsk rural district, Denisov district, Kostanay region, "in connection with the occurrence of anthrax disease in cattle," as reported in the regional akim's decree in the newtimes.kz publication.

Note that this is not the first case of an outbreak of a dangerous disease in the Denisov district of the Kostanay region. In July of this year [2021], in the same area, there was a death of livestock due to anthrax. Earlier it was reported that in Northern Kazakhstan an LLP employee who took part in meat cutting, contracted anthrax.

--
Communicated by:
Mahmoud Orabi
<ahstandards@gmail.com>

[The location of this later cattle death is clearly shown in the July 22nd OIE report on the previous outbreak in QostanyL (https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=36492). It is in northern Kazakhstan and right on the border with Russia.

Late secondary bovine outbreaks are not unexpected and arise from cattle finding bloody soil which is nice and salty. This is why it is so important to properly dispose of all carcasses in any anthrax outbreak. They are curious beasts and will explore anything that catches their interest.

Kazakhstan has been working hard over the past few decades to control anthrax and has largely succeeded. The present situation is but a fraction of what it was. To see their progress, read the following article, which has very useful maps, "Spatio-temporal analysis and visualisation of the anthrax epidemic situation in livestock in Kazakhstan over the period 1933-2016" at https://bit.ly/3HgDnBm.

According to this paper, prior to the outbreaks this year (2021) the last outbreak(s) in Qostany were in 1984-2001. Unintentionally digging up old anthrax graves can present risks if viable spores are brought to the surface. Genotyping these recent cases would help determine what might have happened or not. Again, many thanks to Mahmoud for forwarding this information from Kazakhstan. - Mod.MHJ

